  "text": "The procedure is based on the observation that the dynamic model, in its scale-invariant formulation ͓i.e., using ␤ = 1 when evaluating M ij ͑Eq. ͑6͔͒, yields a coefficient that corresponds to the test-filter scale ␣⌬ rather the grid-filter scale ⌬. That is to say, in practice one approximately obtains a value suitable for c s,␣⌬ instead of c s,⌬ when evaluating the right-hand side of Eqs. ͑7͒ or ͑12͒ with M ij using ␤ = 1. This effect has been observed to be true in numerical experiments of scale dependence both when the coefficient increases with increasing scale, such as when ⌬ approaches the Kolmogorov scale, [CITATION_1] and when the coefficient decreases with increasing scale, e.g., when ⌬ is close to the integral scale. [CITATION_2] This effect can be traced to the fact that, in the Germano identity ͓Eq. ͑3͔͒, the tensor terms relating to the test-filter scale ␣⌬ are significantly greater than the terms relating to the grid-filter scale ⌬ ͑about 4 times greater if ␣ =2͒. Hence these terms relating to the test-filter scale dominate the error term ͓Eq. ͑5͔͒. Using this observation and using ␣ =2, we may write",
